                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Bethene wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Nothing to complain about at all unless you were cheating.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">First let me say that I'm not even flagged for tactics, so I couldn't have done this even if I wanted to.  
<br />

<br />
More to the point though, I have a serious issue with the way this was managed.  Why not just fix the faction problem?!  Why try and hide the fact that there was an issue with the zone?  Why not just come out and say, "Look, there's an exploit based on creating a war between opposing mobs in several zones.  We're looking into if, but until then we have made the following changes to the following zones.  Blah Blah Blah.  It is a bannable offense to try and circumvent these Blah Blah Blah changes and create a mob war where you get exp."
<br />

<br />
Here's a snippet of the patch message:</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>patch message wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">January 22nd, 2004
<br />
----------------------------
<br />

<br />
We have made a few changes to remove some exploits in our continuing effort to remove any loopholes in EverQuest. In this update we have removed the charm exploit in Plane of Tactics by changing the way that charm works. This change should not affect those who use charm in the manner for which it was intended. We have also changed the profit margin of many tradeskill items when sold to NPC vendors. It is our hope that these changes and your continued community efforts will help to put a stop to those who do not wish to play fairly.
<br />

<br />
- Changed Charm spells so that NPCs spell use will now be interrupted once the charm has expired. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"><ol type="1"><li>exploits.   Plural.  What zone are the other ones in?  <li>Are they of the same nature?  <li>How does changing charm 'fix' them?<li>What is the nature of the exploits so that I can report when I see one happening?<li>Ok, so charm should be fine for those using it as it was intended.  That's good to know, but I'll show you in a bit how that sucks.</ol>
<br />

<br />
Now, we have this:</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Brenlo wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Charm Change Clarification
<br />

<br />
Greetings Norrathians,
<br />

<br />
I would like to add this quick clarification to the update message, clarifying the charm effect change.
<br />
If the NPC was in the middle of casting a spell when charm is broken, it will interrupt the spell. After all, the creature is no longer interested in following the orders of a former master. 
<br />

<br />
Brenlo the Charming</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> <a href="http://eqlive.station.sony.com/community/dev_view.jsp?id=60475" target="_blank" class="postlink">From here.</a>
<br />

<br />
First, there's a clarification to the patch.  This shows that the original patch message was admittedly confusing enough to require clarification.  This doesn't really help anyone who's just a casual player of the game (if there are any left..).  You have to go to sony's website or to online message boards like this to find out what's really going on.  But let's just say that the casual player doesn't really care about this thing since it's a detail they just don't go into.
<br />

<br />
However, the clarification to the patch doesn't make sense when you read them both one right after the other.  I mean, after all, isn't the creature no longer interested in following it's own orders once we have charmed it?  Shouldn't it stop everything it's doing the instant it's charmed and start helping us?  I don't care if I'm protected from it's damage spells once it is in my 'group'.  Why is it still trying to cast them on me anyhow when it could interrupt itself, save some mana, and start casting on my actual enemies right away?  Let alone the fact that it would still heal, buff, etc a mob I might be fighting if it happened to be casting something like that.  Aren't the first few seconds of having a charmed mob sometimes very important?
<br />

<br />
The clarification implies that the intent of the charm spell was to cause a mob to immediately change it's course of action when it's charm state changes.  Why does this only work when we lose our mobs?  Why not 'fix' charm so that it does the same thing on both ends of the transaction?
<br />

<br />
But really, I'm most upset about the fact that this exploit isn't being addressed.  The Tactics war is still doable, and apparently that's not the only exploit based on this technique.  It's not like these charm changes actually fixed anything.  As far as I'm concerned: </span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>patch message wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">We have made a few changes to remove some exploits in our continuing effort to remove any loopholes in EverQuest.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> is a total fallacy.  It's quite simply innaccurate.  The exploits are still there and exploitable.  Not only that, but they are telling us that the exploits have been fixed, so are we to assume that they aren't going to do anything to actually fix them?
<br />

<br />
It's just sad.  Why not just fess up, come clean and be straight with us?  The good rule-following people of the world would understand, and the rest, well, they're not changing anytime soon, but at least we would all know what they are up to.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><img src="http://www.blaynesucks.com/images/Bellanfear.gif" border="0" />
<br />
<a href="http://www.therunes.net/forums/viewtopic.php?p=18979" target="_blank" class="postlink">E65.109/LT h+ 2.3kHP 4.3km? ft3 !G e++ o--- T+++ L+ H++(+++)@ f+++ g b c++ t- D !X</a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
