                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">It's an exploit because of simple common sense.  If a non PC controlled NPC does more damage total than you on a mob, the corpse is supposed to poof.  It doesn't in this because of a shoddy fix for raid mobs.  Screw damage.  Screw excessive number of mobs.  People trying to split hairs by getting all lawyer-like and forcing people to quantify reasons so that they can find other reasons to pick them apart in order to "win" an argument about whether it is an exploit or a tactic does not a solid case make.  It's not us that need to be convinced--it's SoE; and when people make an argument like that to justify themselves, it simply weakens their case by making it sound really pathetic, and speeds up SoE's judgement on whether it's an exploit or not if they see the argument.  
<br />

<br />
As to why SoE doesn't just say what the exploits are...think about it.  They don't care what you, one person, will do with the information.  They care a lot more about what people like Yantis would do with that kind of information.  It may be hard to believe, but just because there is an exploit doesn't mean it is public knowledge.  
<br />

<br />
Just to give an example, just in case you don't believe me, then find me a vendor exploit that existed right around when the UIs were being changed--about July-early August 2002 should be the correct time frame.  I know about one at that time because I found it on accident and was too newbish at the time to think it was considered an exploit until I was banned for it.  If you can find it and post the details about it, then I will agree with the opinion of SoE needing to come clean with exploits.  Otherwise I will heartily disagree, as this was able to be fixed decently enough without a ton of people knowing.  It wasn't public knowledge then AFAIK--I seriously doubt it would be public knowledge now.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Sleeping for 65 nights (with 188 interruptions...)
