</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
You made a wrong conclusion there.  I am saying that because people who decide to try to get others--who feel a tactic is an exploit--to limit their reasons for why this or that must be an exploit and then "trap" them to "win" the argument to try to convince them they are wrong aren't proving a single thing.  It's safe to assume that the point of arguing is to convince someone about your opinion on a point being the right one, correct?  So why should someone pick that way to argue when he's just weakening his point?  It's like a parent telling a child to eat his vegetables and the child saying "well I'm only eating French Fries, but that counts!"  I'm not saying arguing is pointless whenever a grey area pops up, I'm just saying if you're going to argue, don't throw out a "counterargument" that just exasperates people.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Security through obscurity is a fallacy.  Period.  Do you really think that Yantis doesn't know about this exploit just because SOE hasn't come out and given some basic details about it?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
It's not about security.  It's about time and knowledge.  Assuming that exploiters know all the exploits in the game is also a fallacy.  Period.  Getting a small amount of people to know so that they can go "SoE, you're slacking here", that's one thing.  Letting every single damn person on every server know, that's asking for a sloppy patch.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">This is a perfect example of why they must disclose the details to these exploits and also provide real and working solutions.  I wasn't playing then.  I have never heard of this exploit.  I am sure that there are plenty of other people who *don't* know about it as well.  Do I think that Yanits and cronies have heard about it?  Absolutely.  Now, if I knew exactly what the details of this exploit were, perhaps I would be able to notice it happening if Yantis was trying to use this.  Since the details and the solution aren't published, that is virtually impossible for me.  However, Yantis can keep trying this and various variations on it until he finds another hole with it or based on it.  More importantly, you have now told me about an exploit that could affect the way I enjoy the game.  How can I go and verify that it's fixed?  I would very much like to do that so I will have the peace of mind that I'm not wasting my time trying to play a game that will prove rather unfulfilling because people can cheat to make my accomplishments meaningless.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
And this is why demanding SoE telling everyone about EVERY SINGLE BUG that pops is a Bad Idea.  I just told you the existence of one vague, extremely specific bug.  That bug was patched in a week from the time it could have popped up in the system, and I only stumbled on it 4 days in.  A bug that WAS rumored about the time this one was in effect (but not one that I can confirm) was that supposedly, items in the Bazaar would disappear when zoned.  There, see?  Another bug!  You don't sound happy to know of the existence of the bug I stumbled on, I don't think you're happy to know about the rumored bug at the time that I'm mentioning now.  So please, tell me why it's a Good Idea for SoE to go public with all the bugs/exploits <span style="font-weight: bold">reported</span> in when you aren't happy about knowing of a bug that definitely doesn't exist anymore.  And the key word here is report...people who exploit on purpose aren't going to report it until they milked it and too many people know about it for it to be profitable for them...so how the hell is SoE going to know until then?
<br />

<br />
I seriously, seriously doubt any exploiters knew about the bug I found anyway.  I can also absolutely guarantee that it definitely absolutely does not work anymore, due to some of the changes they did.  I can also guarantee that any details that I did put up about it after I got banned (because it was already fixed by then) have been long gone for a loonnnnnnnng time.  I can also guarantee you that there is no way in hell a exploiter at the time would stumble upon how it worked, period, simply because it was risky and not profitable in most cases, and because they actually did a Good Job fixing it.
<br />

<br />
Also, something that seems to be not understood, is that for each person that knows the exploit and would report it, there's another someone who would use the exploit who didn't know about it beforehand.  It's nice that you would report it Bellanfear, but now that news of how the Tactics Pit bug works is so public, I can't even XP there anymore.  There is always someone there now in the middle of the night abusing the factions in the Pit.  Even worse, now that more people realize "Oh, Faction can be buggy?" there are even more places they'll think about that have multiple factions that they might want to try to screw over.  More people get screwed over when bugs and exploits are publicly announced than the other way around.  Yes, I can XP elsewhere, but it stinks to have to cross off one more XP spot to sploiters.
<br />

<br />
And here's the thing.  They don't announce the non-public exploits that get fixed.  <a href="http://eq.crgaming.com/viewarticle.asp?Article=4441" target="_blank" class="postlink">Ever seen any mysterious patches that seem kind of...well, minimal?</a>  That's the noise of bugs/exploits that you don't know about getting patched away.  That patch was singled out because that was the patch that fixed what I found.
<br />

<br />
And the absolute worst part...is that the oldest bugs are the bitchiest to fix.  Faction's a relic from the original game.  Any bugs related to it is bound to be older than most expansions.  Just changing the factions sounds so easy...so every time there is a faction related bug, just change the factions!  I mean, hell, it took them 2-3 years just to alter the Spirit of the Shissar's faction so she wouldn't suicide herself, I'm sure altering the faction of half a zone's mobs would take a few minutes.  Right?</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Sleeping for 65 nights (with 188 interruptions...)
