For my personal opinion?  Since I cannot read minds, I would have to take the edge of the coin if possible as I do not know if an exploit is known or not unless I have seen evidence otherwise.  Assumption by itself provides a third choice of "I don't know" in many cases.  For example, the faction bug I can use as an example of a widely known exploit.  I don't think I need to provide evidence of that.  <img src="images/smiles/icon_razz.gif" alt="icon_razz.gif" border="0" />  The vendor bug I mentioned I can conclude is not very widely known because of how it happened, how often I opened my mouth about it, how many people heard my complete explanation, the rumors that were flying at that point in time, and the results of the situation.  For the example of "I don't know", just look at how people reacted before finding the details of how the hell so much plat hit the servers.  People were guessing things from a so-called banker in Befallen (i.e. a questionable unverified exploit) to LDoN adventures (i.e. not an exploit), so was it an exploit that was causing it?  No one knew!  No one had any solid fact until someone in the tradeskill macro exploit camp stopped a plat bot from combining, looked at the combine, and then actually looked at the mysteriously altered price of an item that originally was NOT at 1 silver.  Although guessing what it might have been was fun.
