More people may be thinking about solutions about it, but last time I checked, EQ wasn't exactly open source code.  How exactly is throwing more brains at it going to work when it doesn't control the amount of people who can actually implement the code?  Now, throwing more people at finding bugs, that works.  You don't have to know how the code works to find a bug; you just have to know what is considered normal behavior.  And while that is going on, more people who would abuse the exploit if they find out about it, do find out about it and exploit, thus forcing SoE to do *something* as fast as they can. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Again, I do not advocate the public disclosure of unresolved bugs.  This is a bug that is supposedly solved.  Because there was no public disclosure of the details of this bug that was theoretically solved, I have no way to alieviate my fears of it still being in existance.  That is why I wish SOE would fully disclose the details of the bugs they post patches for.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
/sigh.  OK, let's see if I can actually allay your fears without going step by step on how to do it.   <img src="images/smiles/icon_confused.gif" alt="icon_confused.gif" border="0" /> It's a vendor bug, involving a vendor mining tactic.  (There's plenty of them...)  The point of vendor mining is to access a vendor's hidden inventory.  Merchants do not have a hidden inventory anymore.  While that is not the original way I checked, the fact that they took it out makes it impossible for this bug to even be tested let alone duplicated anyway.  Understood?  That should be more than enough information.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">This is a good reason for SOE to say something such as, "Look there's a bug involving factions and getting mobs to fight one another.  It's a huge bug that's hard to fix, but we have our GMs looking into this.  It's considered a bannable offense to do this.  Please /report anyone you see doing it."  I may have mentioned this before in this thread.  This isn't full disclosure, but it's enough for someone to identify that it's not a good thing.  I would encourage you to 1) /tell those involved that it's an exploit and that they could be banned and 2) /report them if they continue.  Of course since SOE hasn't actually said anything about it like I suggested you will probably be laughed at and stuck with just /reporting them and hoping for the best.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
From what I read from the patch messages, they were trying to do that but screwed up.  Whoever is "fixing" the problem is tackling it from the wrong end because he/she thinks the bug is with charm itself, not factions.  If they were to do that, they would need to actually get the screwup right in the first place. -_-;  Either that, or they threw out "charm" to say "We can't fix the main problem right now, Charm is the only thing we can handle in a reasonable amount of time...and oh BTW, it's an exploit."  In fact, from the patch message today, it really sounds like they meant both charmed NPCs and NPCs casting on something that had charm.  It's not something I can jump to conclusions on right now though.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I would prefer that they did.  It would show me that they are in fact working on making the game better and that they care about their players.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Probably.  I know people who would become dismayed and cancel however if they saw just how super buggy EQ really is though.  Silly people, but still more paying customers nonetheless.  Again, it's one of those "damned if they do, damned if they don't" situations, except that they can't even predict what everyone's true opinion would be.  
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I'm not saying these bugs are easy to fix.  Fixing bugs properly isn't always easy, but it's the right thing to do.  I'm well aware of how difficult it can be.  What I am saying is that they should treat us with respect when it comes to these issues.  However, they are trying to hide their actions and be secretive about all their fixes.  This breeds suspicion and distrust.  Are they really fixing things?  Is there someone on the inside that's making sure these exploits aren't fully resolved?  We certainly can't go out and test them without knowing what they are all about.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I agree somewhat.  It's just that different people have different ideas of respect.  I don't feel they are trying to be secretive--it's hard to be secretive when you don't even appear to understand the bug in the first place.  <img src="images/smiles/icon_razz.gif" alt="icon_razz.gif" border="0" />  Just that if no one realizes about a bug and you fix it anyway, no reason to bring attention to it.  It makes it sound like they're desperate for good news IMO.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Sleeping for 65 nights (with 188 interruptions...)
<br />
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=467231" target="_blank" class="postlink">ZZZzzzzzz...</a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
